_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "CD3 antibody", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9788403511047363, "span": {"begin": 1007, "end": 1019}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6776"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "STAT5", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9887505173683167, "span": {"begin": 1047, "end": 1052}}, {"id": ["mesh:C479163"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "tofacitinib", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9661789536476135, "span": {"begin": 1077, "end": 1088}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3718"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "JAK3", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9860422015190125, "span": {"begin": 1106, "end": 1110}}, {"id": ["mesh:C479163"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "tofacitinib", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9499377608299255, "span": {"begin": 1125, "end": 1136}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6776"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "STAT5", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9937688708305359, "span": {"begin": 1154, "end": 1159}}, {"id": ["mesh:C479163"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Tofacitinib", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9918320775032043, "span": {"begin": 1190, "end": 1201}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:915"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "anti-CD3", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9404575228691101, "span": {"begin": 1224, "end": 1232}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6776"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "STAT5", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9847316741943359, "span": {"begin": 1241, "end": 1246}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CD4+ T cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.5388787388801575, "span": {"begin": 1261, "end": 1273}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3565"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-4", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9278684258460999, "span": {"begin": 1286, "end": 1290}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CD4+ T cells", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.9185501337051392, "span": {"begin": 1307, "end": 1319}}], "text": "IL-4 is a mammalian protein found in Homo sapiens. IL-4 is pivotal in shaping the nature of immune responses. Upon activation, na&iuml;ve peripheral CD4+ T cells begin to synthesize and secrete cytokines. Type 2 helper cells (Th2 cells) produce IL-4, IL-5, IL-6, and IL-13. IL-4 is a 15-kD polypeptide with pleiotropic effects on many cell types. In T cells, binding of IL-4 to its receptor induces proliferation and differentiation into Th2 cells. Th2 cells assist B cells in promoting class switching from IgM to IgG1 and IgE (Choi and Reiser 1998).  STAT5 phosphorylation facilitates the dimerization of STAT5, transport to the nucleus, and gene regulation (Levy and Darnell 2002). DNaseI hypersensitivity sites II (HS) and III (HS) in intron 2 have been identified in several regions of the Il4/Il13 locus. STAT5A binding to sites near HS and HS could provide a mechanism through which STAT5A mediates IL-4 gene accessibility and participates in the induction of IL-4 production (Zhu, et al. 2003). The CD3 antibody-induced phosphorylation of STAT5 can be downregulated by tofacitinib, suggesting that JAK3 inhibition by tofacitinib can downregulate STAT5-dependent cytokine signaling. Tofacitinib was shown to abrogate anti-CD3-induced STAT5 activation in CD4+ T cells and inhibit IL-4 production from CD4+ T cells (Migita, et al. 2011).", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:46:47 +0000 2026"}